{'completion_tokens': 4254, 'response': Response_structure(reasoning='Below is a rough outline of how we can arrive at one feasible set of parameters:\n\n1) Top Speed Requirement (≥ 3.0 m/s):\n   • The wheel’s angular velocity at 3.0 m/s is ω_wheel = v / (r_wheel) = 3.0 / (d/2) = 6/d (rad/s).\n   • The motor speed = gear_ratio × ω_wheel. It must stay below 4000 rpm (≈ 419 rad/s) at 3.0 m/s.\n   • This imposes gear_ratio × (6/d) ≤ 419 → gear_ratio ≤ (419 × d) / 6.\n\n2) Climbing 10° Incline:\n   • Force needed to climb 10° = mg·sin(10°) + (mg·cos(10°)·Crr). For small slopes, sin(10°) ≈ 0.174, cos(10°) ≈ 0.985.\n   • For example, at 10 kg, total climbing force ≈ 10 × 9.81 × (0.174 + 0.015 × 0.985) ≈ 18.5 N.\n   • Wheel torque needed = Force × (d/2). We then ensure that T_wheel ≤ gear_ratio × (motor_torque) × motor_efficiency.\n\n3) Battery Sizing for 30 min at 2.5 m/s:\n   • Rolling friction + drag for a 10 kg robot at 2.5 m/s is small (≈ 4–6 W mechanical). Factoring ≈80% motor efficiency, about 5–8 W electrical.\n   • Over 30 minutes (0.5 h), needed energy ≈ 2.5–4 Wh. A 50 Wh pack provides ample margin.\n\nGiven these constraints, a practical choice might be:\n   • Gear ratio r = 8 (enough to climb while keeping the motor speed below limit at 3 m/s).\n   • Wheel diameter d = 0.15 m (6-inch wheels are a common, manageable size).\n   • Battery capacity C = 50 Wh (more than enough for 30 minutes at 2.5 m/s and gives extra margin).\n   • Robot mass m = 10 kg, which keeps climb torque demands within the motor’s capability.\n\nThese parameters meet all three requirements for speed, gradeability, and half-hour cruising on level ground.', config=ConfigFile(battery_capacity=50.0, gear_ratio=8.0, wheel_diameter=0.15, body_mass=10.0)), 'passed': True, 'evaluation_result': {'v_max_mps': 3.926990816987241, 'T_wheel_Nm': 1.92, 'T_required_Nm': 1.3863023128262497, 'C_required_Wh': 2.2992187499999996, 'C_given': 50.0, 'passed': True}, 'score': 100}
